Today is about understanding why these 2 respected groups have very different conclusions on just how much trouble Social Security is in
Congress count on the experts, like CBO and the Trustees, to help us figure out how to best do that.
Americans want, need, and deserve to be able to count on Social Security. And it‚Äôs up to Congress to make the changes so they can.
We may not all agree on the best way to make Social Security solvent, but we NEED an ACCURATE picture of Social Security‚Äôs financial health
While a plan may be solvent according to the Trustees, it might not even get close if you ask CBO.
With CBO and the Trustees so far apart, it‚Äôs hard to know if a Social Security plan will actually make the program solvent...
Last year their estimates of Social Security‚Äôs shortfall were over 60% apart.  Now they are over 75% apart.
‚Ä¶They also don‚Äôt agree on when Social Security‚Äôs Trust Funds will be exhausted‚Ä¶
CBO & the Trustees don‚Äôt agree on whether Social Security‚Äôs finances got better or worse this year...
‚Ä¶And those differences have a real impact.
Today, CBO & Trustees look at the same historical data but use different approaches & make different assumptions about the future...
Both CBO & Trustees have looked at Social Security‚Äôs finances for yrs.  But Trustees & CBO differ on how much trouble Social Security is in
When it comes to Social Security‚Äôs solvency, the Social Security Trustees‚Äô estimates aren‚Äôt lining up w/ the Congressional Budget Office
Future generations should be able to count on Social Security just like seniors & individuals w/ disabilities do today.
‚Ä¶The longer we wait, the tougher it becomes to fix it.  Congress must make the tough choices based on the best, most accurate info available
We all know how important Social Security is to the millions of Americans who rely on it.  But Social Security is in trouble‚Ä¶
